# Database Schemas — Source of Truth for Data Structure

Every collection or node in the database MUST have a corresponding `.schema.json` file in its service directory. These files document the exact structure, enforce type parity, and serve as the contract between frontend types and backend data.

## Schema File Location

Schema files live alongside their service types:

```
services/
  user/
    user.schema.json    → Documents the Firestore/Realtime structure
    user.types.ts       → TypeScript types MUST match the schema
    user.service.ts
    index.ts
```

## Schema Format

```json
{
  "level": "collection",
  "path": "users",
  "description": "Registered user profiles",
  "schema": {
    "uid": {
      "type": "string",
      "required": true,
      "description": "Firebase Auth UID — used as document ID"
    },
    "name": {
      "type": "string",
      "required": true
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "string",
      "required": true
    }
  }
}
```

## Level Values

| Level | Database | Meaning |
|-------|----------|---------|
| `collection` | Firestore | A Firestore collection (contains documents) |
| `document` | Firestore | A specific document within a collection |
| `node` | Realtime Database | A node in the Realtime Database JSON tree |

## Field Types

Use JSON-compatible type names:

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `string` | Text value |
| `number` | Numeric value (integer or float) |
| `boolean` | true/false |
| `timestamp` | Firestore Timestamp or ISO date string |
| `array` | Array of values (specify `items` for element type) |
| `map` | Nested object (specify `properties` for sub-fields) |
| `reference` | Firestore document reference path |

## Field Properties

| Property | Type | Required | Description |
|----------|------|----------|-------------|
| `type` | string | Yes | Data type of the field |
| `required` | boolean | Yes | Whether the field is mandatory |
| `description` | string | No | What this field represents |
| `default` | any | No | Default value if not provided |
| `items` | object | No | Schema for array elements |
| `properties` | object | No | Schema for map sub-fields |

## Type Parity Rule

The TypeScript interface in `<domain>.types.ts` MUST match the schema exactly:

- Every `required: true` field → non-optional property in the interface
- Every `required: false` field → optional property (`?`) or `| null`
- Field `type` → maps to TypeScript type (`string` → `string`, `timestamp` → `Date | string`, etc.)

```json
{
  "schema": {
    "uid": { "type": "string", "required": true },
    "name": { "type": "string", "required": true },
    "avatarUrl": { "type": "string", "required": false }
  }
}
```

```typescript
export interface UserDocument {
  readonly uid: string
  readonly name: string
  readonly avatarUrl: string | null
}
```

## Naming Convention

All database path segments MUST use **camelCase**. This applies to both Firestore collection names and Realtime Database node names.

| Convention | Example | Status |
|------------|---------|--------|
| camelCase | `studentCredentials`, `userCodes` | Required |
| kebab-case | `student-credentials` | Forbidden |
| snake_case | `student_credentials` | Forbidden |
| PascalCase | `StudentCredentials` | Forbidden |

Single-word paths (`codes`, `students`, `users`) are naturally compliant.

## Rules

- EVERY Firestore collection or Realtime node with read/write access MUST have a `.schema.json`
- Schema files MUST be kept in sync with any database structure changes
- TypeScript types MUST match the schema — type mismatches are bugs
- When adding a new field to the database, update the schema FIRST, then the types
- Schema files are documentation AND contracts — they are reviewed in PRs
- Collection/node names in `path` MUST match the actual database path used in service functions
- All path segments MUST use camelCase — NEVER kebab-case, snake_case, or PascalCase
